{# templates/roadmaps/forex/position-sizing.html.twig #}
{% extends 'base-roadmaps.html.twig' %}

{% block stylesheets %}
    {{ parent() }}
    {{ encore_entry_link_tags('forex_css') }}
{% endblock %}

{% block javascripts %}
    {{ parent() }}
    {{ encore_entry_script_tags('forex_js') }}
{% endblock %}

{% block body %}
    <div class="container">
        <!-- article hero – forex style -->
        <div class="article-hero animate">
            <div class="hero-content">
                <div class="hero-icon">
                    <i class="fas fa-balance-scale"></i>
                </div>
                <h1>Position Sizing: <span>How Much to Risk Per Trade</span></h1>
                <p class="hero-description">
                    Position sizing is the single most important factor in long‑term trading success. Learn how to calculate
                    the perfect lot size based on your account and risk tolerance.
                </p>
                <div class="phase-tag">
                    <i class="fas fa-layer-group"></i> Phase 2: Risk Management · 9 min read
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>

        <!-- introduction -->
        <section class="animate">
            <h2 class="section-title">⚖️ The Cornerstone of Risk Management</h2>
            <p style="font-size: 1.2rem; margin-bottom: 20px;">
                Position sizing determines how many lots (or units) you trade. It’s the link between your stop loss in pips
                and the actual dollar amount you’re willing to lose. Without proper position sizing, a single trade can wipe out
                a large portion of your account – even if your analysis was correct.
            </p>
            <p style="font-size: 1.1rem; color: var(--gray-color);">
                The golden rule: <strong>never risk more than 1–2% of your account on any single trade.</strong> This article
                shows you exactly how to translate that percentage into a lot size, so you can trade with confidence and consistency.
            </p>
        </section>

        <!-- key concepts grid -->
        <div class="rule-grid animate">
            <div class="rule-item" style="border-top-color: var(--forex-color);">
                <h3><i class="fas fa-percent"></i> The 1% Rule</h3>
                <div class="percentage" style="font-size: 1.4rem;">Risk per trade</div>
                <p>Most professionals risk between 0.5% and 2% of their account. This ensures you can withstand a long losing streak without blowing up.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="rule-item" style="border-top-color: var(--forex-color);">
                <h3><i class="fas fa-calculator"></i> Pip Value</h3>
                <div class="percentage" style="font-size: 1.4rem;">Depends on pair & lot</div>
                <p>The monetary value of one pip. For a standard lot (100k) on EUR/USD, 1 pip ≈ $10. For a mini lot, $1; for a micro lot, $0.10.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="rule-item" style="border-top-color: var(--forex-color);">
                <h3><i class="fas fa-chart-line"></i> Stop Loss in Pips</h3>
                <div class="percentage" style="font-size: 1.4rem;">Your exit distance</div>
                <p>The number of pips from entry to stop loss. Combined with pip value, it determines the dollar risk per lot.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="rule-item" style="border-top-color: var(--forex-color);">
                <h3><i class="fas fa-arrows-alt"></i> Lot Size</h3>
                <div class="percentage" style="font-size: 1.4rem;">Standard, Mini, Micro</div>
                <p>Standard = 100,000 units, Mini = 10,000, Micro = 1,000. Choose the lot size that fits your risk parameters.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <!-- deeper dive with formula -->
        <div class="card animate">
            <h3 style="font-size: 1.8rem; margin-bottom: 20px;">🧮 The Position Size Formula</h3>
            <p style="margin-bottom: 20px;">
                To calculate the ideal lot size, use this formula:
            </p>
            <div style="background: #f1f5f9; padding: 20px; border-radius: 16px; margin-bottom: 30px;">
                <p style="font-size: 1.4rem; text-align: center; font-weight: 700;">
                    Lot Size = (Account Balance × Risk %) / (Stop Loss in pips × Pip Value per lot)
                </p>
                <p style="margin-top: 15px;"><strong>Example:</strong> You have a $5,000 account and want to risk 2% ($100) on a trade. Your stop loss is 20 pips. On EUR/USD, 1 pip for a standard lot is $10, so the pip value per lot = $10.</p>
                <p>Lot size = ($5,000 × 0.02) / (20 × $10) = $100 / $200 = 0.5 standard lots, or 5 mini lots.</p>
                <p class="pro-tip" style="margin-top: 15px; background-color: #eef2ff; border-left-color: #3182ce;"><i class="fas fa-lightbulb"></i> Most trading platforms let you enter lot sizes in decimals, e.g., 0.5, 0.01, etc. Use a calculator to avoid mistakes.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <!-- INTERACTIVE TOOL: Position Size Calculator -->
        <div class="card animate" style="margin: 40px 0;" id="position-size-calculator">
            <h3><i class="fas fa-calculator"></i> Position Size Calculator</h3>
            <p>Enter your account details and stop loss to find the recommended lot size.</p>
            <div style="display: flex; flex-wrap: wrap; gap: 20px; align-items: flex-end;">
                <div style="flex: 1 1 150px;">
                    <label for="accountBalance" style="display: block; margin-bottom: 8px; font-weight: 600;">Account balance ($)</label>
                    <input type="number" id="accountBalance" class="cat-input" value="5000" min="100" step="100" style="width: 100%;">
                </div>
                <div style="flex: 1 1 150px;">
                    <label for="riskPercent" style="display: block; margin-bottom: 8px; font-weight: 600;">Risk %</label>
                    <input type="number" id="riskPercent" class="cat-input" value="2" min="0.1" max="5" step="0.1" style="width: 100%;">
                </div>
                <div style="flex: 1 1 150px;">
                    <label for="stopLossPips" style="display: block; margin-bottom: 8px; font-weight: 600;">Stop loss (pips)</label>
                    <input type="number" id="stopLossPips" class="cat-input" value="20" min="1" step="1" style="width: 100%;">
                </div>
                <div style="flex: 1 1 150px;">
                    <label for="pairSelect" style="display: block; margin-bottom: 8px; font-weight: 600;">Currency pair</label>
                    <select id="pairSelect" class="cat-input" style="width: 100%;">
                        <option value="10">EUR/USD (pip ≈ $10 per lot)</option>
                        <option value="10">GBP/USD (pip ≈ $10)</option>
                        <option value="9.5">USD/JPY (pip ≈ $9.5)</option>
                        <option value="10">AUD/USD (pip ≈ $10)</option>
                        <option value="10">USD/CAD (pip ≈ $10)</option>
                    </select>
                </div>
                <div style="flex: 0 0 auto;">
                    <button id="positionSizeCalcBtn" class="btn-outline" style="padding: 12px 30px;">Calculate</button>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div id="positionSizeResult" style="margin-top: 25px; padding: 15px; background: var(--light-color); border-radius: 12px; font-size: 1.2rem; text-align: center;">
                Click calculate to see recommended lot size.
            </div>
        </div>

        <!-- example trade box -->
        <div class="highlight-box animate">
            <h3><i class="fas fa-bolt"></i> Example – GBP/USD Trade</h3>
            <p>You have a $2,000 account and decide to risk 1.5% ($30) on a GBP/USD trade. Your stop loss is 30 pips. For GBP/USD, 1 pip for a standard lot is $10.</p>
            <p>Lot size = $30 / (30 pips × $10) = $30 / $300 = 0.1 standard lots, or 1 mini lot.</p>
            <p>If the trade hits your stop, you lose exactly $30 (1.5% of your account). If you had used a standard lot, you'd lose $300 – 15% of your account!</p>
        </div>

        <!-- pro tip: consistency -->
        <div class="pro-tip animate" style="background-color: #fff5f0; border-left-color: #ff6b35;">
            <h4 style="margin-top: 0;"><i class="fas fa-dragon" style="color:#ff6b35;"></i> The Consistency Edge</h4>
            <p>Professional traders risk the same percentage on every trade, regardless of their confidence. This creates a smooth equity curve and prevents emotional decisions. <strong>Decide your risk % once and stick to it.</strong></p>
        </div>

        <!-- quiz section (conditional) -->
        {% if app.user and quiz is defined and quiz %}
            {# Logged in user – quiz already taken #}
            <div class="quiz-container animate">
                <h3 style="color:white; margin-top: 0;">🧠 You've already taken this quiz</h3>
                <p style="color: #e2e8f0; font-size: 1.2rem;">
                    Your score: <strong>{{ quiz.quizzScore }}%</strong>
                </p>
                <p style="color: #cbd5e0;">
                    You can retake the quiz to improve your score. Click the button below to reset it.
                </p>
                <div class="quiz-actions">
                    <a href="{{ path('app_page_show', { journey: page.journey.name, slug: slug, retake: 1 }) }}"
                       class="btn"
                       style="background-color: #ff6b35; color: white; text-decoration: none;">
                        Retake Quiz
                    </a>
                </div>
            </div>
        {% else %}
            {# Show quiz (interactivity blocked by JS if not logged in) #}
            <div class="quiz-container animate" data-page-id="{{ page.id }}">
                <h3 style="color:white; margin-top: 0;">📝 Test your knowledge: Position Sizing</h3>

                <div class="quiz-question">1. What is the recommended maximum risk per trade for most traders?</div>
                <div class="quiz-options" data-question="1">
                    <div class="quiz-option" data-answer="wrong">5–10%</div>
                    <div class="quiz-option" data-answer="wrong">10–20%</div>
                    <div class="quiz-option" data-answer="correct">1–2%</div>
                    <div class="quiz-option" data-answer="wrong">0.1%</div>
                </div>

                <div class="quiz-question">2. If you have a $10,000 account and risk 2% with a 20‑pip stop loss, what is your dollar risk?</div>
                <div class="quiz-options" data-question="2">
                    <div class="quiz-option" data-answer="wrong">$100</div>
                    <div class="quiz-option" data-answer="correct">$200</div>
                    <div class="quiz-option" data-answer="wrong">$400</div>
                    <div class="quiz-option" data-answer="wrong">$20</div>
                </div>

                <div class="quiz-question">3. What is the pip value for one standard lot on EUR/USD (approximately)?</div>
                <div class="quiz-options" data-question="3">
                    <div class="quiz-option" data-answer="wrong">$1</div>
                    <div class="quiz-option" data-answer="correct">$10</div>
                    <div class="quiz-option" data-answer="wrong">$100</div>
                    <div class="quiz-option" data-answer="wrong">$0.10</div>
                </div>

                <div class="quiz-question">4. Which lot size represents 1,000 units of currency?</div>
                <div class="quiz-options" data-question="4">
                    <div class="quiz-option" data-answer="wrong">Standard</div>
                    <div class="quiz-option" data-answer="wrong">Mini</div>
                    <div class="quiz-option" data-answer="correct">Micro</div>
                    <div class="quiz-option" data-answer="wrong">Nano</div>
                </div>

                <div class="quiz-question">5. Why is consistency in position sizing important?</div>
                <div class="quiz-options" data-question="5">
                    <div class="quiz-option" data-answer="correct">It prevents emotional decisions and creates a predictable risk profile</div>
                    <div class="quiz-option" data-answer="wrong">It guarantees profits</div>
                    <div class="quiz-option" data-answer="wrong">It allows you to increase risk after losses</div>
                    <div class="quiz-option" data-answer="wrong">It reduces the need for a stop loss</div>
                </div>

                <div class="quiz-actions">
                    <button id="quiz-submit" class="btn">Get score & submit</button>
                </div>
                <div class="quiz-result"></div>
            </div>
        {% endif %}

        <!-- next steps in phase 2 (risk management) -->
        <section style="margin: 60px 0;">
            <h2 class="section-title" style="text-align: center;">📘 Continue mastering risk</h2>
            <div class="next-steps">
                <a href="{{ path('app_page_show', { journey: 'forex', slug: 'stop-losses-take-profits' }) }}" class="next-card">
                    <i class="fas fa-shield-alt"></i>
                    <h3>Stop Losses & Take Profits</h3>
                    <p style="color: var(--gray-color);">Learn the golden rule of protecting your capital.</p>
                </a>
                <a href="{{ path('app_page_show', { journey: 'forex', slug: 'risk-reward-ratio' }) }}" class="next-card">
                    <i class="fas fa-chart-pie"></i>
                    <h3>Risk‑Reward Ratio</h3>
                    <p style="color: var(--gray-color);">Set realistic targets and build a profitable strategy.</p>
                </a>
                <a href="{{ path('app_page_show', { journey: 'forex', slug: 'psychological-traps' }) }}" class="next-card">
                    <i class="fas fa-brain"></i>
                    <h3>Common Psychological Traps</h3>
                    <p style="color: var(--gray-color);">Avoid emotional mistakes that ruin accounts.</p>
                </a>
            </div>
        </section>
    </div>
{% endblock %}
